Fire and Rescue Services' (FRS) resources were being stretched to the limit on Wednesday as various fires two of them considered major blazes ravaged areas across the Mother City.Officials say the fires in the Simon's Town area were spreading fast and had led to road closures and various homes being evacuated, including 20 residents from a retirement home.&nbsp;No injuries were reported, but more than 1 000 homes in and around Simon's Town have been evacuated, officials said.https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rNKw7eS12f8 The City s Fire and Rescue Services are still actively protecting property and lives throughout the City of Cape Town area, currently dealing with 11 fire incidents. The two major fires at the moment are the Somerset West and Simon s Town fires, said FRS s Liezl Moodie.While crews were still busy with damping-down operations in Somerset West, with helicopters assisting ground crews with flare-ups and hot spots, the City had to move quickly to send out more crews to Simon s Town where a fire was raging out of control. https://twitter.com/hashtag/CTfires?src=tren&amp;data_id=tweet%3A819200533496008704 whatsapp-audio-2017-01-11-at-162306-2ogg-codecsopusHuge plumes of smoke were billowing over Simon s Town and surrounding areas, making visibility poor. Aerial support is still in operation, assisting ground crews and firefighters by waterbombing in the inaccessible areas. The City s Disaster Operations Centre was activated to co-ordinate the response to the fires.According to Disaster Risk Management s Mandy Thomas, the SANDF, SAPS and metro police were deployed to the areas already evacuated. Metro Police, SPCA and law enforcement have assisted with the evacuation of domestic animals, said Thomas, who advised residents with respiratory problems to stay away from the area.&quot;Glencairn Express Way and Arsenal roads were closed to traffic. Kommetjie rRad is congested and Traffic Services are on the scene to assist with traffic flow. The fire started above Kommetjie Road in Ocean View on Wednesday morning. The fire was inaccessible and spread from Ocean View across the mountain in the direction of Da Gama Park.&nbsp;</p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p> </p>